title: Updating a Service Plan
---

<strong><%= modified_date %></strong>

_This page assumes you are using cf CLI v6._

Application development and maintenance on a PaaS sometimes requires updating a service plan due to a new service's availability, some services being withdrawn from availability or other events on the platform. This article describes the best way to update a service plan on the Application Cloud platform.

1. Run the `cf env` command and obtain your database credentials by searching in the `VCAP_SERVICES` environment variable:

    <pre class="terminal">
    $ cf env my-db-app
    Getting env variables for app my-db-app in org My-Org / space development as admin...
    OK

    System-Provided:
    {
      "VCAP_SERVICES": {
        "example-db-n/a": [
          {
            "name": "test-777",
            "label": "example-db-n",
            "tags": ["mysql","relational"],
            "plan": "basic",
            "credentials" : {
              "jdbcUrl": "jdbcmysql://aa11:2b@cdbr-05.example.net:3306/ad_01",
              "uri": "mysql://aa11:2b@cdbr-05.example.net:	34/ad_01?reconnect=true",
              "name": "ad_01",
              "hostname": "cdbr-05.example.net",
              "port": "1234",
              "username": "aa11",
              "password": "2b"
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    </pre>

2. Create a tunnel using [Service Connector](../service-connector/index.html#using-service-connector). E.g. `cf service-connector 49099 y4alksjwoinlx2.service.consul:49099`

3. Back up your data (using MongoDB as an example): `mongodump --host 127.0.0.1:49022 --authenticationDatabase D4T4B453 --username U53rN4m3 --password P455w0rD --db 1PNxGDOCifaaHnr5 --out=dbbackup/dump`

4. [Create](../devguide/services/managing-services.html#create) a new service.

5. [Bind](../devguide/services/application-binding.html#bind) that service to your application or create [service-keys](../devguide/services/service-keys.html#create).

6. Run the `cf env` command again, to obtain your new database credentials by searching in the `VCAP_SERVICES` environment variable:

    <pre class="terminal">
    $ cf env my-db-app
    Getting env variables for app my-db-app in org My-Org / space development as admin...
    OK

    System-Provided:
    {
      "VCAP_SERVICES": {
        "example-db-n/a": [
          {
            "name": "test-777",
            "label": "example-db-n",
            "tags": ["mysql","relational"],
            "plan": "basic",
            "credentials" : {
              "jdbcUrl": "jdbcmysql://aa11:2b@cdbr-05.example.net:3306/ad_01",
              "uri": "mysql://aa11:2b@cdbr-05.example.net:	34/ad_01?reconnect=true",
              "name": "ad_01",
              "hostname": "cdbr-05.example.net",
              "port": "1234",
              "username": "aa11",
              "password": "2b"
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    </pre>

7. Create a tunnel to the new service using [Service Connector](../service-connector/index.html#using-service-connector). E.g. `cf service-connector 50000 joiw209fnj2jx2.service.consul:50000`

8. Restore your data, (example with MongoDB): `mongorestore --host 127.0.0.1:50000 --authenticationDatabase D4T4B453 --username U53rN4m3 --password P455w0rD --db D4T4B453 dbbackup/dump/D4T4B453/`

9. Delete your old service instance.
